BEGIN_PGML
Does the table show that [`x`] and [`y`] have a linear relationship?

>> [@DataTable(
  [
    [[PGML('[`x`]'),
      rowbottom => '2',
      midrule => '1',],
     PGML('[`y`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[0]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[1]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[1]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[2]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[2]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[3]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[3]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[4]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[4]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[5]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[5]]`]'),
    ],
  ],
      align => '*{2}{r}',
      valign => 'middle',);@]* <<

[_]{$no}{5}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
As each [`x`]-value increases by [`1\text{,}`] the [`y`]-values increases by [`[$diff[0]]\text{,}`] then [`[$diff[1]]\text{,}`] then [`[$diff[2]]\text{,}`] then [`[$diff[3]]\text{,}`] then [`[$diff[4]]\text{.}`] So this table shows that [`x`] and [`y`] do not have a linear relationship.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

